Zoran Zaev, Prime Minister of Macedonia, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko deposited their vote in the Macedonia referendum on a change of name of the country that would open the way for joining NATO and the European Union in Strumica (Macedonia) on September 30, 2018.
In front of Parliament, in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, prepared a small stage and removed chairs in front of tents planted by those who were going to boycott the referendum.
"We are in favour of joining NATO and the EU, but we want to do it with our heads high, not through the back door," Kavadarkov said.
"We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
