"The sea belongs to us": a landlocked Bolivia hopes that the court will reopen the route to the Pacific
Sailors guard a naval headquarters in La Paz.
In public buildings they wave navy blue flags.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the naval bases show the motto: "The sea belongs to us by right,
It's a duty to get it back."
Across Bolivia, a land without sea, they still vividly recall the coast lost to Chile in a bloody conflict over resources that took place in the 19th century, in addition to the longing to re-sea the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes may be the greatest in decades, as Bolivia is awaiting a resolution by the International Court of Justice on October 1, after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, is waiting for the result with a positive vision," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will observe the ruling of the International Court of Justice on large screens throughout the country, in the hope that the court in The Hague will pronounce itself in favor of Bolivia's claim that, after decades of intermittent talks, Chile has an obligation to negotiate to grant Bolivia a sovereign way out of the sea.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia, who is waging a controversial battle for reelection next year, also has a lot to say about Monday's resolution.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean," he promised at the end of August.
However, some analysts believe that it is unlikely that the court will decide in favor of Bolivia and that the situation would change little if it did.
The United Nations agency based in the Netherlands has no power to award Chilean territory and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the ruling of the International Court of Justice comes only six months after the closing arguments indicates that the case "was not complicated," said Paz Zárate, Chilean expert in international law.
Far from promoting the cause of Bolivia, it may have been hindered over the past four years.
"The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration," said Zárate.
In addition, he suggested that Morales' belligerent rhetoric has undermined any residual Chilean goodwill.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to speak at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to hold talks after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision-making was unusually quick.
On Monday, Bolivia will be offered "an extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile" and the possibility of "ending 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits," he said.
Also, Calzadilla denied that Morales, who is still one of the most popular presidents in Latin America, used the maritime issue as a political crutch.
"Bolivia will never give up its right to access the Pacific Ocean," he added.
"The resolution is an opportunity to see that we have to leave the past behind."
