John Edward: Language skills are fundamental to the citizens of the world
Independent educational institutions in Scotland have a track record of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary test results that is reinforced by individual and collective successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in the schools.
As Nelson Mandela said: "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his tongue, it reaches his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that, if you want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you cannot rely solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year's exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the qualifier tables, with the highest pass rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages received an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 SCIS centres, showed that 72% of students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of those studying German, 69% of those studying French and 63% of those studying Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as they are considered a fundamental competence that both children and young people will certainly need in the future.
Currently, as a subject, languages are considered to be at the same level as CTIM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and everywhere.
A survey carried out in 2014 by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills revealed that, of the reasons given by employers for the difficulties they faced in filling jobs, 17% were attributed to the shortage of language skills.
Language skills are therefore becoming increasingly indispensable in preparing young people for their future careers.
Potential job opportunities that require languages are on the rise, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career that someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last a lifetime.
Being able to communicate directly with persons from foreign countries will allow that person to automatically anticipate competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov among more than 4000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation. It was also established that the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for today's children.
If they know several languages, especially those in developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the most classical modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools he or she will always be able to choose between several languages taught by specialized teaching staff in this field.
Scotland's independent educational centres devote every effort to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills necessary to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At present, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be of vital importance for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be regarded as "competences for international communication".
Independent colleges will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges
