North Korea says that "there is no chance" that they will be disarmed first unilaterally if they have no confidence
On Saturday, the North Korean Foreign Minister informed the United Nations that the continuation of the sanctions deepened his distrust in the United States and that there was no possibility that his country would unilaterally renounce nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho stated to the annual General Assembly of the international body that North Korea had taken "important measures of goodwill" over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile testing, dismantling nuclear testing facilities and committing to the non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we did not receive any similar response from the United States," he said.
"If we do not have confidence in the United States, we cannot have confidence in our national security, and, in those circumstances, there is no possibility that we will first disarm unilaterally."
Although Ri repeated North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" denuclearization formula that rewards the country as it takes gradual steps, his statement is important, as he did not simply reject a unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump following the first summit between an active US president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim pledged to work for the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" and Trump guaranteed North Korea's security.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the Korean War of 1950-53, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first renounce its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States has insisted on denuclearization in the first place and has increased pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its purpose in a coercive manner, even by objecting to a declaration of end of war," Ri said.
"The idea that sanctions can make us fall on our knees is a chimera of people who don't know us.
The problem is that the continuation of sanctions deepens our mistrust."
Ri made no mention of the plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which was announced by the U.S. leader at the United Nations at the beginning of the week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and Moon Jae, the leader of South Korea, over the past five months, and added: "If South Korea had been the party interested in denuclearization instead of the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such a stalemate."
Even so, the tone of Ri's speech was radically different from last year's speech, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to direct North Korea's missiles to American soil after the "malignant president" Trump, on a suicide mission, called Kim "a rocket man."
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in advancing towards disarmament, but said that much remained to be done and that further sanctions were needed until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no time frame set for this: "It can take two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for his progress.
However, as U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: "The imposition of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and without non-compliance until we realize the definitive and fully verified denuclearization."
The Security Council has unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea since 2006, in an attempt to cut funding for Pyongyang ballistic and nuclear missile programmes.
Pompeo chatted with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and later commented that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying that progress had been made, but, a few hours later, North Korea reported that its "requirements were those of a mobster."
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States applied the "corresponding measures."
He said Kim had told him that the "corresponding measures" he was looking for were the security assurances Trump had promised in Singapore and steps towards normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
Thanks to a new course this year at Harvard University, all college students sleep more in an attempt to fight the growing sexist culture of studying all night long by drinking caffeine.
One professor discovered that students at the world's number one university often have no idea about basic self-care.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard School of Medicine, and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital designed the course, believed to be the first in his class in the United States.
His motivation to start the course arose after giving a talk about how sleep deprivation affects learning.
"At the end of the course, a girl came up and asked me why she just found out about this now, in her senior year.
He said that no one had ever told him about the importance of the dream, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the basic concepts about how good sleep habits contribute to academic and sports performance, as well as improving general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard School of Medicine and executive director of the university's health services, noted that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students barely slept during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of sleeplessness on sports performance and the importance of establishing a routine to go to sleep.
In another section, participants are informed how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, embolism, depression, and cancer.
Afterwards, a campus icon with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
"We know that it will not change the behavior of students instantly.
However, we believe they have the right to know, just as anyone has the right to know the health effects of smoking tobacco," added Professor Czeisler.
He stated that the culture of pride in "sleeping the night" still exists and added that modern technology and the increasing pressure to which students are subjected meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Sleeping long enough and a good quality dream should be "the secret weapon" of students to fight stress, tiredness and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, since sleep deprivation causes the brain to generate a feeling of hunger, so they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes the previous year during his first year at Harvard.
He pointed out that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to expand it to the entire campus.
He hoped that the next step would be to ask all graduate students to complete a similar curriculum before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler's recommendation is for students to think about setting up an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by the screens of electrical appliances and LEDs, which can alter circadian rhythms, so they would end up having trouble falling asleep.
