HIV/AIDS: China reports 14% more new cases
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
More than 820 000 people are affected in the country, according to the health authorities.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, some 40,000 new cases were reported.
The vast majority of these were sexually infected, which is a change from the past.
Traditionally, HIV spread rapidly in parts of China as a result of transfusions of infected blood.
However, the number of people who contract HIV in this way has declined almost entirely, the Chinese health authorities said at a congress in Yunnan province.
Every year, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China increases by about 100,000 people.
Sexual transmission of HIV is a serious problem in the LGBT community in China.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but the LGBT collective suffers a lot of discrimination.
Because of conservative values in the country, studies have estimated that 70% to 90% of men who have sex with other men will end up marrying women.
Many of the transmissions of diseases are because they do not use adequate protection in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV medicines as part of an attempt to address the problem.
Maxine Waters denies that a member of her staff leaks data from Republican Party senators and claims that these are "dangerous lies" and "conspiracy theories"
Representative Maxine Waters criticized on Saturday the allegations that a member of her staff had posted the personal data of three U.S. Republican Party senators on Wikipedia's legislative pages.
The Los Angeles Democrat claimed that these allegations were driven by "extreme right" commentators and websites.
"Lies, lies and more vile lies," Waters commented in a Twitter post.
