The leak took place sometime after the three senators had questioned Kavanaugh.
Conservative sites, such as Gateway Pundit and RedState, reported that the IP address identifying the source of the publications was associated with the Waters office and made public the data of a Waters staff member, according to the Capitol.
"This baseless accusation is completely false and an absolute lie," Waters continued.
"The member of my staff, whose identity, personal data and security have been affected as a result of these fraudulent and false accusations, was not at all responsible for the leaking of this information.
This baseless allegation is completely false and an absolute lie."
Waters' statement elicited immediate criticism on the Internet, including from former White House press secretary Ari Fleischer.
"You deny this information with anger," Fleischer wrote.
"This suggests not the temperance needed to become a Member of Congress.
When someone is accused of something he didn't do, he shouldn't be angry.
You must not rebel.
You must not question the motives of the accuser.
He must remain calm and calm."
It seems that Fleischer wanted to compare Waters' reaction to the Democrats' criticism of Judge Kavanaugh, whom the detractors accused of appearing too angry during Thursday's appearance.
Omar Navarro, a Republican candidate who aims to derail Waters in the mid-term elections, also expressed his opinion on Twitter.
"If it's true, it's very serious," she tweeted.
In his statement, Waters said his office had alerted "the relevant authorities and law enforcement entities to these fraudulent allegations."
"We will make sure the authors are discovered," he continued, "and that they are legally held responsible for all these destructive and dangerous actions for all my staff members."
