What is the Global Citizen Festival? Have you managed to reduce poverty?
This Saturday, New York will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual music festival, where an impressive poster of stars gathers for an equally impressive mission: ending poverty in the world.
This year, in its seventh edition, the Global Citizen Festival will see tens of thousands of people moving to the Great Lawn of Central Park to enjoy performances such as those of Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to raise awareness about the actual goal of the event: ending extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which began in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international awareness group that hopes to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
If you want to receive a free ticket to the event (unless you can afford a VIP ticket), concert attendees have had to complete a series of tasks or "actions", such as volunteering, sending emails to a world leader, making a phone call or anything else that will help raise awareness about your goal of ending poverty.
However, what has the Global Citizen achieved 12 years after reaching its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding with a free concert a genuine way of persuading people to take action or is it just a form of so-called "clictivism," which is called the stance we take when we think we are doing something really useful by signing an online petition or sending a tweet?
Since 2011, Global Citizen claims to have recorded more than 19 million "actions" of its supporters in favor of a large number of diverse goals.
Thanks to these actions, they claim to have got world leaders to announce commitments and policies worth more than $37 billion, which will impact the lives of more than 2250 million people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements that emerged from its shares, of which at least $10 billion has already been disbursed or raised.
The group estimates that guaranteed funds have had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people worldwide.
Among the most important commitments is "The Power of Nutrition", a UK-based partnership of investors and implementers united with a common commitment to "help children grow and develop with their full potential." To this end, they have set out to provide Rwanda with $35 million to help end the country's malnutrition after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens partners.
"Thanks to the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and Global Citizens partners like you, we can mark a small milestone in the history of the social injustice of malnutrition," Tracey Ullman, Ambassador of "The Power of Nutrition," told the crowd during a concert in April 2018 in London.
The group also stated that, after having carried out more than 5000 actions to try to improve nutrition in the UK for mothers and children, the government announced funding for a project, Power of Nutrition, with which 5 million women and children will benefit from nutrition-related interventions.
In response to one of the frequently asked questions on your website about what we believe can be done to remedy extreme poverty,
a collaborator of Global Citizen replied: "It will be a long and hard road and, on many occasions, we will stumble and fall.
But, as the human rights and anti-apartheid movements have already achieved, we will achieve our goals, because we are stronger together.
Janet Jackson, the Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monáe are some of the performances that we will have at this year's New York event, which will be hosted by Deborra-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman.
