US ambassador accuses China of "bullying" with "propagandistic announcements"
A week after an official Chinese newspaper published a four-page ad in a U.S. newspaper promoting the mutual benefits of US-China trade, the U.S. ambassador to China accused Beijing of using the U.S. press to spread its propaganda.
Last Wednesday, U.S. President Donald Trump referred to China Daily's payment supplement at the Des Moines Register, Iowa's most-selling newspaper, after accusing China of wanting to interfere in the November 6 U.S. Congressional elections, something China strongly denies.
Trump's accusation of Beijing's attempt to influence the US elections marked what U.S. officials indicated to Reuters as a new phase in a growing campaign launched by Washington to pressure China.
While it is common for foreign governments to publish advertisements to promote their commercial activities, Beijing and Washington are currently blocked in a growing trade war that has led to higher tariff levels on imports from both sides.
China's compensatory tariffs that were applied at the beginning of the trade war were thought to fall to exporters in states like Iowa, which supported Trump's Republican Party, according to Chinese and U.S. experts.
Terry Branstad, the US ambassador to China and the former governor of Iowa, who is one of the leading exporters of agricultural products to China, said Beijing had harmed American workers, farmers and entrepreneurs.
As Branstad wrote in an op-ed at the Des Moines Register on Sunday, China "is further intensifying this pressure with advertising publications in our free press."
"To try to spread their propaganda, the Chinese government uses America's cherished tradition of free speech and free press by attempting to publish a paid ad in the Des Moines Register," Branstad wrote.
"On the other hand, in the street kiosk where we are here in Beijing, there are only a few dissenting voices and no real reflection of the disparate views that people in China can have about the worrying trajectory that their country's economy is taking, as the media is controlled by the strong pressure of the Chinese Communist Party," he wrote.
He added that "one of the most relevant newspapers in China eluded the offer to publish" his article, although he did not specify which newspaper it was.
