World Wide Web inventor plans to launch a new Internet to compete with Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a new company that tries to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrupt is the latest technology legend project, a company based on Berners-Lee's Solid open source platform.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and which people will have access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt is to "dominate the world."
"It has to be now," he said about the startup.
"It's a historic moment."
The application uses Solid's technology to enable users to create their own "online personal data storage" or a POD.
It can contain lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library and other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available in a browser and at the same time.
One thing that is unique in personal online data storage is that the user is the one who completely decides who can access what type of information.
The company calls it "personal training through data".
Inrupt's idea, according to the company's CEO, John Bruce, is to incorporate the resources, processes and skills necessary for Solid to reach everyone.
For the time being, the company is made up of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform that IBM bought, some of the developers included in the template that were hired to work on the project and a community of volunteer programmers.
As of this week, technology developers from around the world could create their own decentralized apps with the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to "Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce a radical change where all their business models are completely modified overnight.
"We're not asking permission."
In a publication in Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote about Inrupt that "its mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new website created on Solid."
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has played a very influential role in the debate on net neutrality.
Even though he is launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will continue to be the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I am incredibly optimistic about this next era of the web," Berners-Lee added.
Bernard Vann: the clergyman who won a Victoria Cross in World War I
The only clergyman of the Church of England who won a Victoria Cross during World War I as a fighter has been honored in his hometown 100 years later.
Lieutenant Colonel Reverend Bernard Vann was awarded this award on 29 September 1918 in the attack of Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, a sniper killed him four days later and never knew that he had been granted the greatest British military honour.
On Saturday, his two grandchildren discovered a commemorative stone at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of them, Michael Vann, said it was "of a special symbolism" that the stone was discovered exactly 100 years after the battle that made him deserve the decoration of his grandfather.
According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion through the Canal de Saint-Quentin "through a thick fog and under the intense fire of machine guns and cannons."
He then ran to the line of fire and, with the "greatest courage", pushed the line forward before reaching a cannon with one hand and toppling three of the detachment.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, only a month after the war ended.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather's actions were "so great that I will never be able to live up to him, but they were very instructive."
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, also deposited a wreath of flowers after the parade, which featured the band Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said that "it was a privilege for him to be part of the parade" and added that "the value of a true hero is evident when he is shown such a large backing."
