The new German warship, postponed again
The new German Navy frigate should have been commissioned in 2014 to replace the old ships of the Cold War era, but it will not be done until at least next year due to faulty systems and the progressive increase in costs, local media reported.
The delivery of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the ship that heads the new frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class, has now been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit newspaper, a statement by a military spokesman.
The ship should have joined the Navy in 2014, but the problems that arose after the delivery screwed up the conclusion of the ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class requested by the Navy in 2007 will replace the old Bremen-class frigates.
We know that they will include a powerful cannon, a set of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some invisibility technologies, such as radar, infrared and very small acoustic signals.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods so that they can be deployed for up to two years away from the ports of origin.
However, the continuous delays have caused the innovative ships (which were supposed to allow Germany to project its power overseas) to be out of date by the time they start serving, says Die Zeit.
The unfortunate F125 frigate held headlines last year, when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into operation and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It has been the first time the Navy has returned a ship to a shipyard after its delivery.
Little was known about the reasons behind the return, but the German media cited a number of crucial "software and hardware defects" that left the ship virtually useless if sent to a combat mission.
The deficiencies in software were particularly important, as the Baden-Wuerttemberg class ships will be operated by a crew of some 120 sailors: half of the personnel in the former Bremen class frigates.
It was also found that the ship is overweight, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy's ability to add future updates.
The 7000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz is believed to be twice as heavy as other ships of similar class used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to defective hardware, the price of the entire project, including crew training, has also been a problem.
It is believed to have reached €3.1 billion ($3.6 billion), instead of the initial €2.2 billion.
The problems attributed to the new frigates are of particular relevance in the light of recent warnings about the reduction of Germany's naval power.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the defense committee of the German parliament, acknowledged that the Navy is "leaving without ships capable of deploying."
The officer said that the problem has become worse over time, because the old ships were discharged, but have not been replaced with others.
He regretted that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class frigates were able to join the Navy.
The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
This new research, which has been carried out in a state of the Scottish Highlands, tries to discover how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
Everything that is found is expected to shed more light on the behavior of the only flying mammals and help guide the upcoming conservation activities.
The study, carried out by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow the common bats and sopranos, as well as the coastal bats of Daubenton and long-eared browns of the Inverewe Gardens on Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in strategic locations of the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile research with portable detectors.
Experts will analyze the sounds that are collected in the recordings to discover the frequency of calls of bats and which species do.
A report and a habitat map will then be produced to create a detailed picture of the environment and its behaviour.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of grasslands and how forests should be maintained for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined considerably over the last century.
They are under threat from the construction and development that affects their nests and the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and electrical wiring can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticide papers and other chemical treatments of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind,
but, because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes to achieve their goal.
They use a sophisticated ecolocation technique that locates ants and obstacles on their flight route.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has 10 trained experts in the field, who regularly conduct surveys, nest inspections and, at times, rescues.
The organization has opened even the first and only reserve dedicated to bats from Scotland in the state of Thrave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The property manager, David Thompson, says it's the ideal territory for them.
"Here, in Thrave, we have a fantastic area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, many old trees and all the right habitat.
However, there are still many unknown things about bats, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us to better understand what they need to develop."
He stressed the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance tasks within the properties, since a breeding colony could be destroyed inadvertently and 400 females and young could be killed, which would mean annihilating an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them, as well as destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer in charge of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to collaborate.
He said, "We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species about which we don't know how their populations evolve."
