Syria is ready for the refugees to return, says Foreign Minister
Syria states that it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and requests help to rebuild a country devastated by a war that has been going on for more than seven years.
In a speech before the UN General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that the country's conditions were improving.
"The situation on the ground is now more stable and secure thanks to the progress that has been made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate the areas destroyed by terrorists to try to restore normalcy.
All the conditions for the voluntary return to the country of refugees who had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures affecting their daily lives and livelihoods are already in place.
The UN estimates that since the war began in 2011, more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country.
There are another six million people still living in the country who need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem acknowledged that the Syrian regime would appreciate assistance in rebuilding the devastated country.
But he also emphasized that he would not accept conditional aid or aid from countries that promoted insurgency.
